 6. a review of the evidence (if any) tendered in defence of the claim.

Despite some difference in the judicial approach of Finkelstein J and Gordon J in Jefferson Ford , the Court is prepared to follow the observations of Gordon J as providing a practical guide to the interpretation of s 31A of the Court Act. The conflict between Gordon J and Rares J in Jefferson Ford (see [129], [73]) and which was not resolved in Wills , relating to whether judges retain a general discretion to enter summary judgment under s 31A, is irrelevant to the current judgment, and accordingly it is unnecessary for the Court to consider the conflicting judicial opinions.

